{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14263"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14263"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.35,0.47,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6958"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77483"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"607"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2157"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31329"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of a suddenly painful right eye. He reports photophobia, clear tearing and blurred vision. His son attends daycare and was recently home sick. He has psoriatic arthritis and takes diclofenac 25mg three times per day. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His vital signs are within normal limits. His right eye is red, with marked ciliary injection. The pupil is small and poorly reactive to light. His left eye has no abnormality. Visual acuity in the right eye is 6/12, compared to 6/6 in the left eye. Intraocular Pressure is 21mmHg in the right eye and 16mmHg in the left eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical antibiotic eye drops","Topical intraocular pressure lowering drops","Slit lamp examination","Urgent referral for retinal detachment","Computed tomography of the orbits"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of anterior uveitis (also known as iritis). This covers inflammation of the iris and the anterior ciliary body. A red, acutely painful eye with photophobia and a constricted pupil are typical features, and it may be acute, chronic or recurrent. The next appropriate step in management is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eslit lamp examination\u003C/strong\u003E. This will confirm the diagnosis by revealing cells and flare in the anterior chamber, which are pathognomonic for anterior uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotic eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for bacterial conjunctivitis, but the presentation here is not consistent with this diagnosis. Conjunctivitis typically causes a red eye with sticky discharge, but without the severe pain, photophobia, and visual changes seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent referral for retinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated based on the presenting symptoms. Retinal detachment typically presents with floaters, flashes of light, and a curtain-like loss of vision, none of which are described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of the orbits\u003C/strong\u003E is not the next step for this presentation. While imaging may be useful in cases of orbital cellulitis or other space-occupying lesions, the clinical picture here is more consistent with an anterior segment inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical intraocular pressure lowering drops\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the intra-ocular pressure is normal in both eyes. Assessment of intraocular pressure is a fundamental part of ocular examination alongside visual acuity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with slit lamp examination, treatment typically involves topical corticosteroids (prednisolone acetate 1%) and cycloplegic agents. It\u0027s also important to consider and investigate potential underlying systemic causes of iritis, such as ankylosing spondylitis, inflammatory bowel disease, sarcoid, HL-B27, syphilis or reactive arthritis. In this case, psoriatic arthritis would be the clue for this patient as it is associated with anterior uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute iritis typically presents with a red, painful eye, photophobia, and a constricted pupil.","Slit lamp examination is crucial for diagnosing acute iritis, revealing cells and flare in the anterior chamber.","Acute iritis can be associated with systemic conditions such as ankylosing spondylitis, inflammatory bowel disease, and reactive arthritis."],"references":["Read R, Feldman B, Tsakiris K et al. Anterior Uveitis. Eye Wiki. 2022. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Acute_Anterior_Uveitis","Agrawal RV, Murthy S, Sangwan V, Biswas J. Current approach in diagnosis and management of anterior uveitis. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2010 Jan-Feb;58(1):11-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2841369/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77483"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14263"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77483"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T23:37:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T14:47:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6958"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94444"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a